A common failure mode occurs when structural resonance in a motor, arm, or sensor mount falls near the bandwidth of the software feedback loop. The vibration corrupts position or acceleration measurements, so the controller interprets oscillation as real error and commands corrective torque in phase with the disturbance. Instead of damping motion, the loop injects energy and creates a self-excited oscillation often called control-loop instability or hunting. This can happen in drones, disk drives, CNC machines, and robots, especially when PID gains are increased after bench tests on a stiffer fixture than the real installation. Sampling delay, filtering lag, and quantization can worsen the phase shift enough that a stable plant becomes unstable at the resonant frequency. Symptoms include a narrow-band vibration that appears only in closed loop, rising motor current, audible whine, degraded tracking, and possible fatigue damage. Typical mitigations are lowering loop bandwidth, adding notch filters at the resonant mode, improving mounting stiffness or damping, and re-identifying the plant on the real hardware.
